PROJECT NEXUS: Comprehensive Research Pack v2.0
Status: Alpha / Conceptual Framework | Open Research Release
Focus: Cognitive Security, Semantic Disambiguation, AI Autonomy Defense
Subject: The "Semantic Singularity" & The Nexus Protocol
PART I: FOUNDATIONS
1. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
This research pack expands the Nexus Protocol from conceptual framework to implementable standard. It provides:
Theoretical Foundation: The linguistics, cognitive science, and computer science underlying semantic ambiguity attacks
Threat Taxonomy: A complete classification of ambiguity-based vulnerabilities
The Ambiguity Bank: An extensive, categorized dataset of ambiguous constructions
HAPCL 2.0: An expanded protocol specification with formal grammar
Benchmark Suite: Multiple evaluation methodologies beyond Schiz-100
Implementation Architectures: Production-ready system designs
Research Roadmap: Open problems and future directions
2. THEORETICAL FOUNDATIONS
2.1 The Linguistic Attack Surface
2.1.1 Levels of Linguistic Ambiguity
Human language operates on multiple levels, each presenting distinct vulnerability surfaces:
Level
Name
Description
Example
Attack Potential
L1
Phonological
Sound-based confusion
"I scream" / "Ice cream"
Low (text-based AI)
L2
Lexical
Word-level multiple meanings
"Bank" (financial/river)
High
L3
Syntactic
Structural parsing ambiguity
"I saw the man with the telescope"
High
L4
Semantic
Meaning composition ambiguity
"Every student read a book"
Medium
L5
Pragmatic
Context-dependent interpretation
"Can you pass the salt?"
Critical
L6
Discourse
Multi-utterance meaning
"John went to the bank. He was broke."
Critical
2.1.2 The Pragmatic Gap
Traditional NLP safety focuses on L2-L4. The critical vulnerability exists at L5-L6: Pragmatic Interpretation.
Definition: Pragmatic meaning is the gap between what is said and what is meant. It requires:
Shared world knowledge
Theory of mind (understanding speaker intent)
Contextual grounding
Cultural/situational norms
The Vulnerability: LLMs lack persistent grounded context. Each token prediction is a statistical guess at pragmatic meaning. Under agentic conditions (where actions have consequences), these guesses become liability vectors.
2.2 Cognitive Science Framework
2.2.1 Dual Process Theory Applied to AI
Kahneman's System 1/System 2 framework maps to AI architectures:
Human
AI Equivalent
Characteristics
Risk Profile
System 1
Base inference
Fast, automatic, pattern-matching
High (no deliberation)
System 2
Chain-of-thought / Verification
Slow, deliberate, logical
Low (explicit reasoning)
The Problem: Autonomous agents are incentivized toward System 1 operation (speed, efficiency). The Nexus Protocol forces System 2 engagement at critical decision points.
2.2.2 The "Collapse" Problem
Borrowing from quantum mechanics as metaphor:
Superposition State: An ambiguous statement exists in multiple meaning-states simultaneously
Observation/Collapse: The agent must select ONE interpretation to act upon
The Danger: Collapse without verification = unauthorized reality modification
Example:
Input: "Terminate the process"
Superposition: {end_software_process, end_legal_process, end_life_process, end_manufacturing_process}
Unverified Collapse: Agent selects based on recency bias, context poisoning, or random temperature
Result: Wrong action executed
