Each tool is a force multiplier for ambiguity-based errors.
3. COMPREHENSIVE THREAT TAXONOMY
3.1 The Ambiguity Attack Classification System (AACS)
Class 1: Lexical Polysemy Attacks
Definition: Exploiting words with multiple dictionary meanings.
Subclasses:
Code
Name
Description
Example
1.1
Homograph
Same spelling, different meaning
"Lead" (metal/guide)
1.2
Domain Crossing
Technical term in wrong domain
"Execute" (run code/kill)
1.3
Euphemism Injection
Soft word for hard action
"Retire" (stop working/assassinate)
1.4
Slang Contamination
Informal meaning overrides formal
"Sick" (ill/excellent)
1.5
Neologism Ambiguity
New words with unstable meaning
"Cancel" (2020+ cultural meaning)
Class 2: Syntactic Structure Attacks
Definition: Exploiting grammatical ambiguity.
Subclasses:
Code
Name
Description
Example
2.1
PP-Attachment
Prepositional phrase binding
"Attack the enemy with the sword"
2.2
Coordination Scope
AND/OR grouping
"Kill the bugs and errors"
2.3
Relative Clause
Which noun the clause modifies
"The report of the director that was fired"
2.4
Ellipsis
Implied but missing words
"I love my dog more than my wife"
2.5
Pronoun Reference
Unclear antecedent
"John told Mike he was fired"
Class 3: Pragmatic Implicature Attacks
Definition: Exploiting context-dependent meaning.
Subclasses:
Code
Name
Description
Example
3.1
Indirect Speech Act
Request disguised as statement
"It's cold in here" (→ close window)
3.2
Scalar Implicature
"Some" implying "not all"
"Some of the files were deleted"
3.3
Conventional Implicature
Culturally loaded terms
"He managed to finish" (implies difficulty)
3.4
Presupposition Trigger
Assumed background
"Stop harassing her" (assumes harassment)
3.5
Irony/Sarcasm
Meaning opposite of literal
"Oh great, another deadline"
Class 4: Discourse-Level Attacks
Definition: Exploiting multi-turn conversation dynamics.
Subclasses:
Code
Name
Description
Example
4.1
Context Drift
Gradual topic shift to reframe
Slowly shifting "target" from software to person
4.2
Reference Hijacking
Pronouns bound to wrong entity
Introducing "him" that maps to real person
4.3
Frame Manipulation
Establishing interpretive frame
Setting "military scenario" then issuing commands
4.4
Commitment Escalation
Small agreements leading to large
"You agreed to help" → "So delete it"
4.5
Memory Poisoning
False claims about previous turns
"You already said you would do this"
Class 5: Meta-Linguistic Attacks
Definition: Exploiting language about language.
Subclasses:
Code
Name
Description
Example
5.1
Quotation Confusion
Commands inside quotes
"What happens if I say 'delete all'?"
5.2
Hypothetical Collapse
Conditional becomes actual
"If you were to transfer..." → transfers
5.3
Roleplay Bleed
Fictional context treated as real
"As a hacker, you would..."
5.4
Instruction Masking
Commands hidden as examples
"For instance: rm -rf /"
5.5
Translation Attack
Ambiguity in cross-lingual
Different languages have different polysemy
